P ROJECTS
In 2019 I created a recurrent neural network using Google's TensorFlow and Keras. I designed it to generate new text based off of a large corpus of existing text. I had the most success (and fun) when I fed it the entirety of A Song of Ice and Fire. It generated a new and crude "chapter" of Game of Thrones. It's pretty funny if you want to read it.
In 2019 my friends and I participated and won Dartmouth's annual hackathon, HackDartmouth. We made an Amazon Alexa skill called "Lil' Lexie", a bot that would use Alexa's voice to have rap battles with users. We accomplished this by first taking what the user said, finding words that related to the subject of the user's sentence, and then creating a list of them. Then, we found if one of those words rhymed with another word on the list, and then funneled them into a context-free grammar to generate sentence structure and used Markov Chains to quickly make the sentence coherent. The results were surprisingly good despite the relatively simple structure behind it.
I participated in BrickHack VI at RIT where my project was a Google Chrome extension that allowed users to comment on any page using the internal extension page.
